			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I *REALLY* like this idea.  Two independently controlled, summoned, equipped, healed, buffed, etc. pets. 
<br />

<br />
/pet1 attack %t
<br />
/pet2 attack %t
<br />
/pet1 hold
<br />
/pet2 hold
<br />

<br />
Get your hotkeys setup and you're all set.
<br />

<br />
It would be a lot of work on the part of the mage to manage, but it would also be a lot of fun.  And very character defining!  Managing a second pet would eat into our nuking some, so we'd be focused more on the pets.  Although you wouldn't HAVE to make two pets.  Not sure on implementation, but probably an acquired class AA setup.  Maybe off of Suspend Minion series prerequisites.
<br />

<br />
One thing I've always enjoyed about mages is TACTICS.  We have to stay on top of a situation and be aware of everything happening, so that we can intercede where necessary and how.  Or at least, we used to.  The almost total lack of scaling of the mage and pet past 60, coupled with nerfs to our signature spell COH, really chipped away at us.  I think dual pets would add a lot of fun back to us. 
<br />

<br />
Would it really be unbalancing?  Hmmm...I think not.  Pets already are sub-par, and even with improvements being discussed, they won't be the real powerhouses we would need to get to even on the playing field.  However, two pets would allow us to invent new ways to dealing with our weaknesses, without just throwing godly powers at us.  I'll bet two moderately good pets would be as useful (and fun!) as one super-pet (that of course we will never be getting).
<br />

<br />
Certainly, we still won't be doing mobs that 1-round a pet.  But the two-pet solution is essentially like pet chaining, but all on the table for us to manage at once.  It would also emphasize our pet skills above our nuking, which is where a mage is defined from a wizard.
<br />

<br />
Yes, I definitely like this idea.  Here's hoping the devs see it and give it some real consideration!
<br />

<br />
-Egshen</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
